In this notebook:

Explore variation in samples with principal components analysis (PCA)

Perform PCA on subsets of features

Remove outliers manually

Specify new subsets of data

The following functions are introduced:


  • study.interactive_pca and study.plot_pca
    These funcitons perform Principal Components Ananlysis on user-selected subsets of samples and features. Samples are colored according to a dictionary saved in the Create A New Study notebook.

  • study.drop_outliers
    After setting the outlier attribute in study.metadata.data the samples labelled outliers are removed from study.expression.data and study.splicing.data

  • study.plot_gene and study.plot_event
    These plot the distribution of gene expression or $\psi$ in each phenotype.

  • study.merge_boolean_metadata_columns takes mulitiple boolean (True/False) columns and returns the logical OR of these columns.

Interactive PCA

Choose feature type, sample subset, and feature subsets to perform PCA.

By default, the most variant features among the samples selected are used to perform PCA.

HTML widgets allow user interaction:

Alternatively (for presentations like this for example) users can set the range of options at the function call.

interactive_pca options:


  • Select data_type (expression/splicing), sample_subset, feature_subset from pull-down menus.

  • Transpose with featurewise to examine relationships between features

  • Use custom lists from the internet (Dropbox?) or local file paths with list_link and the custom feature subset.

  • Choose other principal components to plot with sliders.

  • Plot violin plots with plot_violins

  • Label samples

sample_subsets include:

  • All boolean columns in study.metadata.data

  • Phenotypes

  • Pooled samples

  • Outliers

feature_subsets include:

  • Everything annotated in Gencode

    • Protein coding genes

    • lncRNA

    • snoRNA/snRNA/tRNA...

    • Pseudogenes

  • And some things that are not

    • RNA-binding proteins

    • Neural celltype lineage markers from (Fluidigm) biomark panel.

    • Transcription factors

Summary

With minimal coding users can interact and visualize complex patterns in their data.

Users can:

  • Examine expression of interesting genes among phenotypes

  • Modify parameters with interactive HTML widgets

  • Select the inverse of sample subsets.

  • Modify sample/feature subsets on the fly.

  • Use feature lists from web sources.
